<dl id="n47144f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n47" href="#n47144f">N47 (VI.B.40)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n47all.htm#n47144f"> 144(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> my answerer / (proxy) <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n47144f"><li>FW 410.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/lexpA.htm#n47144f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pA/l39pA.htm#n47144f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n47144f">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="pAd12ydash" href="../../FF/fdra/pda.htm#pAd12ydash">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pA/pAd12.htm#n47144f">Draft: III&sect;1A.12</a>+'&apos; </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Transferred via <a name="sh6007s" href="sh6all.htm#sh6007s">Sheet vi-07(s)</a> </mm> <blockquote class="sources">In dynastic times the Egyptians dropped the barbarous custom of burying alive with dead kings a number of slaves, whose souls were intended to wait upon the soul of their king in the Other World. Instead they substituted figures called <i>ushabtiu</i> or &lsquo;answerers&rsquo; made of stone, wood, fa&iuml;ence, &amp;c., which when called upon by the deceased would turn into full-grown men or women and do all that he commanded to do. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD3" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD3"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd Ed (1909) lxxviii, xcii</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also N38 (VI.B.32):169</mm> </dd></dl>
